Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1908, Albert Einstein's quantum theory of light introduced the idea that light has both wave-like and particle-like properties, a concept that became a foundational part of quantum mechanics.

Einstein's theory resolved contradictions in classical wave theory and provided evidence for the emerging quantum theory. It earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics and was crucial in the development of quantum mechanics, showing that light behaves as both a wave (in its ability to interfere and diffract) and a particle (in its ability to transfer energy in discrete units).

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
With respect to Presidents‚Äô prerogative to nominate their cabinet and federal judges, the best indication of what I will do in the future is what I have done in the past. I have strived to be consistent over the arc of time and respected the fact that elections have consequences.

My role as a United States Senator is different than that of the President. Winning an election allows the President to pick their cabinet, make executive appointments and nominate federal judges for lifetime seats. When you look at my history regarding these matters, you will find that I honor this concept.

Every nominee will have to acquit themselves well during the confirmation process by answering difficult questions and having their actions scrutinized. This process should be the same for every nominee. In the past, Democrats have, on occasion, abused the confirmation process. If I believe this is happening again, I will speak out loudly.

Generally speaking, I vote for confirmation regardless of party or personal feelings because that is my Constitutional role as a Senator. I will do the same for President Trump‚Äôs nominees.

The American people have spoken loudly, and President Trump won decisively. I consider this matter closed.

text: 2/9 In 2017, during my first term, I teamed up with Senator Orrin Hatch to help Emery County achieve this vision. We built on their groundwork‚Äîengaging local voices, listening to Utahns, and striving for consensus where public land designations often bring division.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: 1/9 For two decades, Emery County leaders worked to balance public land priorities‚Äîavoiding top-down designations that have often left locals feeling unheard. The Emery County Public Lands Council, elected officials, and stakeholders pushed to protect sacred tribal sites, recreation areas, and spaces for grazing and hunting, aiming to avoid becoming another Bears Ears or Grand Staircase-Escalante.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: THREAD: Yesterday, SITLA announced a historic land exchange, finalizing the Emery County Land Bill I worked hard to pass, ensuring access to a million acres of public lands and generating millions in funding for Utah‚Äôs schools. This concludes a journey I began with Senator Hatch shortly after I arrived in Congress. Here's why this matters. #utpol #PublicLands

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: 3/10 Our goal was simple but ambitious: create a plan that put Emery County's landscapes under the best management for the long haul. We had dozens of meetings, open houses, and discussions with diverse stakeholders‚Äîconservationists, outdoor recreation groups, ranchers, and local leaders‚Äîto make sure everyone was heard.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: 4/9 After years of refining the bill, we achieved something rare: broad bipartisan support. With backing from local officials, Utah leaders, and major outdoor recreation advocates, the Emery County Land Bill offered something for everyone‚Äîa remarkable accomplishment in public lands policy.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: 7/9 The school land trust exchange, a key part of the bill, is now coming to life. With this exchange agreement, nearly 100,000 acres of school trust land will generate millions to support Utah‚Äôs public schools and allow for the efficient management of new wilderness and recreation sites.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: 5/9 In 2019, Congress passed the John D. Dingell, Jr. Conservation, Management, and Recreation Act, which included our Emery County bill. This created the San Rafael Swell Recreation Area, expanded Goblin Valley State Park, and established the Jurassic National Monument‚Äîhome to one of the world's richest deposits of Jurassic-era fossils.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text:
6/9 For Utahns, this law delivers tangible benefits:

The San Rafael Swell Recreation Area invites outdoor enthusiasts, climbers, and families to explore one of Utah's hidden gems.
The Jurassic National Monument preserves our prehistoric heritage and draws educational and scientific interest from around the globe.

Name: Curtis, John R.
text: 8/9 With Bears Ears and Grand Staircase-Escalante back in the news, yesterday‚Äôs announcement proves that the best way to solve our public lands issues is through congressional action. Name: Suozzi, Thomas R.
text:
Today marks #WorldDiabetesDay , a day that honors the contributions of Sir Frederick Banting, one of the pioneers who discovered insulin in 1921.¬†

Back in 1923, when insulin was patented, Banting and his fellow researchers made a groundbreaking decision. They declined to put their names on the patent and sold it to the University of Toronto for just $1. Their perspective was clear: it was unethical for a doctor to profit from a life-saving discovery, and they wanted to ensure that everyone who needed insulin could afford it.

Fast forward over a century, and it‚Äôs clear that Banting and his colleagues would be dismayed to witness how their life-saving medication has become synonymous with pharmaceutical price gouging. Stories of individuals with diabetes forced to ration their insulin‚Äîsometimes with fatal consequences‚Äîare all too common. This is a moral outrage.

Now, more than ever, it‚Äôs crucial to safeguard the Inflation Reduction Act, which enables Medicare to negotiate directly with drug manufacturers and caps insulin prices at $35 for Medicare recipients. We must stand firm against any efforts to roll back these essential protections. Together, we can ensure that life-saving medications remain accessible for all.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1777, after 16 months of debate, the Continental Congress adopted the Articles of Confederation. 

The Articles created a weak central government, reflecting the Patriots' fear of centralized power. Congress, a single house with one vote per state, could conduct foreign affairs, raise an army, and declare war, but lacked the power to tax. Amendments required unanimous approval from all states. Maryland's ratification in 1781 marked the Articles' official approval by all 13 states.

By 1787, the system was deemed inadequate, prompting the creation of a new constitution. A secret convention convened in Philadelphia to draft a new framework, leading to the U.S. Constitution in 1789, which replaced the Articles of Confederation. This shift marked a transition from rule by a king, to states' sovereignty, and finally to a unified people forming a federal government. This evolution encapsulated the American Revolution's transformation.

Name: Pfluger, August
text:
I am incredibly honored to have the support of my colleagues as the next Chairman of the Republican Study Committee. 

This organization has been led by incredible mentors of mine, including Speaker Mike Johnson, Majority Leader Steve Scalise, Jim Jordan, Senator-Elect Jim Banks, and current Chairman Kevin Hern. I want to thank Chairman Hern for his leadership of the RSC over the last two years and for effectively utilizing our slim majority in the House of Representatives to push back against the Biden-Harris Agenda.
 
As Chairman, I am committed to championing policies that protect our freedoms, ensure national security, and foster economic prosperity for all Americans. The RSC will continue to be the conservative backbone of the House, pushing for a strong, resilient America that can stand up to both foreign adversaries and domestic challenges. 

Together, we will work to advance conservative principles and make life better for hardworking Americans, while holding the line on runaway spending, promoting energy dominance, and securing our borders.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals who rise above the ordinary and inspire us all. Today, we shine a spotlight on a man whose extraordinary service to our nation and tireless advocacy for veterans continue to inspire and uplift our community‚Äîmeet this week's Hometown Hero, David A. Christian. 
 
A Levittown native and Woodrow Wilson graduate, David is known throughout the country as the youngest, most decorated Vietnam War officer. David rose to the rank of Captain by 20, serving as an Airborne Ranger and Green Beret, whose bravery was legendary‚Äîleading missions deep into enemy territory, dismantling machine-gun nests armed with only hand grenades and a bayonet, and discovering enemy bases. His heroism earned him nominations for every valor award, including the Medal of Honor and seven Purple Hearts. 
 
David‚Äôs sacrifices were not without cost. Wounded in action seven times and severely burned by napalm, he returned to Bucks County with a new mission: to fight for his fellow veterans. Drawing from his pain and experience, he authored the nation‚Äôs first laws addressing Agent Orange exposure and Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD), setting a standard for veteran care that remains the ‚Äúlaw of the land.‚Äù

His leadership and expertise earned him appointments under four U.S. Presidents and a role as Senior Advisor to the U.S. Senate on Foreign Relations. David also played a pivotal role in creating the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C., raising $9 million to honor his fallen brothers.
 
To this day, David continues to serve our community and veterans, even establishing Victor Six, a non-profit focused on improving our local veterans' mental and physical well-being. The program provides free health and fitness training, fostering resilience, camaraderie, and hope while addressing the critical issue of suicide prevention within the veteran community. For his remarkable service, last May, David was inducted into the National Military Officers Hall of Fame. 
 
As we continue to reflect on Veterans Day, David‚Äôs story reminds us of the extraordinary courage, sacrifice, and service of our nation‚Äôs veterans. Honoring these heroes is not reserved for a single day, it is a responsibility we must uphold every day.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: For years, Massachusetts residents have dreamed of replacing the Cape Cod bridges, enabling West-East Rail, making our roads safer, and improving our transit systems. Thanks to the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law, we‚Äôre seeing those dreams become reality.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: With over $600 million, we‚Äôre¬†riding full steam ahead to replace the North Station Rail Drawbridge and build West-East Rail service between the Berkshires, Springfield, Worcester,¬†and Boston.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: It‚Äôs been three years since we passed the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law. And since then,¬†I‚Äôve¬†been hard at work unlocking funds to¬†build the bridges, roads, rails, and bike lanes to the future. I‚Äôm proud to share some of the progress we‚Äôve made‚Äîand ready for fights ahead.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: It‚Äôs been a historic year,¬†in which we secured¬†$1.3 billion to replace the Sagamore Bridge. And with an additional $1.1 billion to replace bridges in Lowell, North Adams, Amesbury,¬†and all across the Commonwealth,¬†we‚Äôre ushering in a new era for transportation in the Bay State.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: We‚Äôre¬†also¬†jumpstarting initiatives to help close the state‚Äôs digital divide, redesign the Allston-Brighton corridor of I-90, support pedestrian & bicycle safety,¬†and¬†make 14 MBTA Green Line stations fully accessible.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: Thanks to additional funding to support environmental remediation efforts and supercharge our transition to clean energy, Massachusetts is leading the way in the fight for a green future.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: Between @WRTA continuing the longest-running fare-free service pilot in the United States and @pvta‚Äôs transition to low-emission and no-emission buses, Massachusetts is laying the groundwork for the future of public transit.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: And with¬†over¬†$3¬†billion for public transit, we‚Äôre returning the T to a state of good repair‚Äîand¬†building a sustainable, long-term future for transit in the Commonwealth.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: From improving public transit to expanding broadband access, the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law is hard¬†at work in communities across the Commonwealth. Let‚Äôs keep working to ensure that the BIL helps us make our visions a reality for years to come.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: We‚Äôve helped deliver $107 million to 23 school districts across Massachusetts through the EPA Clean School Bus program. With more than 160 clean school buses, the BIL is¬†delivering a cleaner, greener future for our children‚Äîon and off the bus.

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: Lastly, the¬†BIL¬†is giving new life to transportation hubs across Massachusetts. Thanks to this funding, we‚Äôre able to modernize Logan Airport Terminal E,¬†rework¬†the I-90/I-495 interchange in MetroWest, and improve transportation corridors in¬†Roxbury, Lynn, and Fall River.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1974, researchers sent humanity‚Äôs first deliberate radio message into space, aimed at potential extraterrestrial life. 

The transmission, broadcast from Puerto Rico‚Äôs Arecibo Observatory, marked the completion of an upgrade to the facility's radio telescope. The message, created by astronomers Carl Sagan and Frank Drake, was directed at the M13 star cluster, located about 21,000 light years away. It contained a simple visual message, including the DNA formula, a diagram of the solar system, an image of the Arecibo telescope, and a stick figure of a human.

Though no response came, the researchers, including Cornell University‚Äôs Donald Campbell, were not expecting one. The transmission was more symbolic, demonstrating humanity‚Äôs technological capability. The Arecibo Observatory, which played a pivotal role in radio astronomy for six decades, tragically collapsed in 2020 due to structural failures. It was decommissioned in 2022, but its legacy in planetary science and space research endures.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1978, Jim Jones, leader of the Peoples Temple, led a mass murder-suicide at their remote commune in Jonestown, Guyana, resulting in 909 deaths, including a third who were children. 

Jones founded the Peoples Temple in the 1950s. Years later, the church faced accusations of financial fraud, abuse, and mistreatment of members. Facing increasing criticism, Jones moved his followers to Guyana , promising a utopian society. However, life in Jonestown was harsh, with members working long hours under strict control, including surveillance, forced confessions, and mock suicide drills. Jones, increasingly paranoid and addicted to drugs, believed the U.S. government was conspiring against him.

Former Temple members and concerned families convinced U.S. Congressman Leo Ryan to investigate Jonestown. The visit began peacefully, but several residents requested to leave. Jones became alarmed and ordered an ambush. Ryan and four others were killed as they attempted to leave the airstrip.

Back in Jonestown, Jones instructed followers to gather for what he called a "revolutionary act." Children were poisoned first, followed by adults, while armed guards prevented anyone from fleeing. The next day, authorities discovered hundreds of bodies at the commune, many grouped together. Some members had escaped into the jungle, and others survived because they were in a different part of Guyana at the time.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1863, President Abraham Lincoln delivered the Gettysburg Address at the dedication of a military cemetery in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, following the Battle of Gettysburg. 

This battle, fought four months earlier, was one of the Civil War's bloodiest, with over 45,000 casualties. It marked a turning point in the war, as Confederate General Robert E. Lee‚Äôs defeat ended the Southern army's invasion of Northern territory.

The speech was just over 270 words, beginning with the phrase, ‚ÄúFour score and seven years ago.‚Äù Lincoln's famous conclusion emphasized the ongoing struggle for liberty: "The world will little note, nor long remember what we say here, but it can never forget what they did here. ‚Ä¶ It is for us the living, rather, to be dedicated here to the unfinished work ‚Ä¶ that from these honored dead we take increased devotion to that cause for which they gave the last full measure of devotion ‚Ä¶ that this nation, under God, shall have a new birth of freedom‚Äîand that government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth.‚Äù

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
**FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE**
Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson Joins Ranking Member @repdavidscott  in Urging Swift Action on #DisasterAid for #Farmers and Families

Washington, D.C. ‚Äì [11/19/2024]  Today, Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson (IL-01) joined Ranking Member David Scott (GA-13) in calling for immediate action from Congress to provide critical disaster aid to farmers and families affected by recent natural disasters. Congressman Jackson issued a statement urging lawmakers to prioritize relief efforts and pass a comprehensive disaster aid package to assist agricultural communities that are struggling to recover from severe weather events, including floods, hurricanes, and droughts.

‚ÄúThe devastation caused by recent natural disasters has left farmers and rural families across the country in urgent need of support,‚Äù said Congressman Jonathan Jackson. ‚ÄúThese hardworking men and women are the backbone of our nation's agricultural industry, and it's our responsibility to ensure they have the resources to rebuild and continue their vital work. I stand with Ranking Member David Scott and my colleagues in calling for swift, comprehensive disaster relief that will provide farmers with the financial assistance and tools they need to recover, rebuild, and ensure food security for future generations.‚Äù

‚ÄúFrom #Georgia to #Illinois, from cornfields to cotton fields, communities are reeling from the effects of storms and droughts. This is not just an agricultural issue, it‚Äôs an economic and humanitarian issue. We must pass disaster relief to help these families regain their feet and rebuild stronger than before.‚Äù

Congressman Jackson and Ranking Member Scott have also committed to working with their colleagues on both sides of the aisle to ensure that disaster aid reaches those who need it most and that the relief measures are as effective and timely as possible.

‚ÄúNow is the time for Congress to come together and put people over politics,‚Äù Jackson continued. ‚ÄúWe cannot afford to let these critical relief efforts be delayed. Our farmers' and rural families' lives and livelihoods depend on it.‚Äù

The call for swift action comes as lawmakers prepare for upcoming votes on disaster relief legislation, and Jackson and Scott are committed to pushing for a comprehensive solution that meets the needs of affected communities nationwide.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
Earlier today I was unanimously elected as the next Chairman of the Congressional Western Caucus, the second largest membership caucus in the House of Representatives. There are over 100 members of the bipartisan caucus that focuses on western and rural issues such as energy, mining, timber, agriculture, ranching, water, and public lands. I‚Äôm grateful for the opportunity to serve as Chairman of the Congressional Western Caucus and continue fighting for rural America. A big thank you to Chairman Newhouse for his strong leadership ‚Äî he‚Äôs laid a solid foundation, and I‚Äôm ready to build on it as we tackle the challenges ahead.

The Western Caucus has been a strong voice in Washington for over 30 years, and I‚Äôm excited to work with the Trump Administration and our members to deliver real results for the folks who call rural America home. The Caucus has a unique position to be able to work closely with @realdonaldtrump‚Äôs administration, who shares our values on the need to expand American energy, take the yoke of federal bureaucracy off of the American farmer and rancher, and to unleash the potential of rural America by getting Washington D.C. out of the way. Name: Daines, Steve
text:
What‚Äôs changed since the May hearing on the RFK Stadium bill?

In short, any stigma around the logo is gone. Blackie Wetzel‚Äôs legacy has been honored. A foundation is in the works. This iconic Native American imagery has been restored to a place of honor.

Here‚Äôs the full story‚Ä¶

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
3 yrs ago MTn Don Wetzel shared an inspiring story with me.

His father, Blackie Wetzel, Chairman of the Blackfeet Tribe, designed a logo modeled after historic Tribal leaders, including¬†Chief Two Guns White Calf.

It ended up being the iconic logo used by Washington's NFL team. https://t.co/D38XQpm30u

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
Don also shared his top priority‚Äîto use the iconic logo to help promote a philanthropic foundation to support Native American causes.

But at the time, team leadership wouldn't talk to him.

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
At the time, this logo‚Äîa depiction of real people, NOT a caricature‚Äîhad just been "canceled" along with the old team name.

When Don & I visited he was clear‚Äîthis logo was a symbol of strength. It was a point of pride in Indian Country, and it should be recognized as such.

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
On top of that, there was no reason for the team to erase the logo from their history or be ashamed of their connection to Indian Country.

In social media posts, on merchandise & more, the logo was censored as if a Native American Chief was an obscene image.

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
So, in May at a National Parks subcommittee hearing on the RFK bill, I brought Don, and now his son Ryan's, demands to the table.

The team and the NFL needed to right this historic wrong.

Name: Daines, Steve
text: For years the @Commanders own social media rarely mentioned the franchise‚Äôs storied history and winning legacy‚Äîbut since May they‚Äôve highlighted it dozens of times. https://t.co/1CVLFQGYcj

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
The @NFL posted poorly photoshopped images to hide the logo while promoting previous Super Bowl champions.

It wasn't until after my hearing that they again celebrated historic players' successes while sporting the proud logo. https://t.co/A9RNbWzqFu

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
@fox5dc¬†even blurred the logo on a local broadcast showing historical clips from the team‚Äôs heyday, treating the warrior likeness like a lewd or obscene image.

After I called them out for this outrageous practice, Fox 5 immediately stopped erasing the logo from their coverage. https://t.co/U2q5BngXps

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
In Oct, an NFL retailer was selling a Darrell Green legacy shirt that crudely erased the logo.

Again I called out this ridiculous practice & not only did¬†@Commanders leadership assure me this wouldn't happen again, a few days later players wore similar shirts WITH the logo. https://t.co/A7BYd63F5a

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
I‚Äôm glad the team & the league finally understand what millions of fans, including the Wetzels & the Blackfeet Tribe, all see. 

The logo isn't offensive & it isn't derogatory. It's an honorable & realistic depiction. It's a tribute & appreciation of Native American history.

Name: Daines, Steve
text: Over the past several months we've also worked with the @Commanders' corporate sponsors to encourage them to wholeheartedly support the Tribe's request to restore the logo‚Äîincluding in merchandise sales.

Name: Daines, Steve
text:
Additionally, Ryan, the¬†@Commanders¬†& the¬†@NFL¬†are having productive conversations about creating¬†a foundation to benefit Native American causes.

With this commitment,¬†we are on a clear path to finally achieving¬†what Don Wetzel set out to do¬†for the good of Indian Country.

Name: Daines, Steve
text: I‚Äôm proud of the progress we‚Äôve made and voted to advance the RFK bill out of committee today. I look forward to continuing to watch the @Commanders & the @NFL honor this iconic part of their history!
